# Project Overview
- This project uses Next.js for frontend with React Server Components and SSR.
- Supabase is the backend database with real-time data features.
- TypeScript is used throughout for strong typing and better development experience.

# React & Next.js Standards
- Use React Server Components and Next.js SSR features by default.
- Limit 'use client' directive to small interactive components only.
- Always provide loading and error UI states for async data fetching.
- Memoize expensive or repeated computations with useMemo.
- Wrap pure components with React.memo for performance.
- Use dynamic imports for large or rarely needed components.
- Follow atomic design principles; keep UI components small and reusable.
- Apply TailwindCSS classes consistently; avoid inline styles unless atomic override.

# Supabase Integration
- Use Supabase React hooks correctly (e.g., useQuery, useSubscription).
- Explicitly type all data returned from Supabase APIs with TypeScript interfaces.
- Properly clean up subscriptions and listeners in useEffect hooks.
- Handle errors gracefully with try/catch and fallback UI for all async functions.

# Code Style & Quality
- Use 2-space indentation, single quotes for strings, and mandatory semicolons.
- Adopt kebab-case for component and file names (e.g., my-component.tsx).
- Write clear, meaningful variable and function names using camelCase.
- Document all exported functions with JSDoc, including parameters and return types.
- Avoid TODOs, placeholders, or unfinished code in completions.
- Separate concerns: UI components, data hooks, and utilities in different files.

# Performance & Optimization
- Optimize image loading with lazy loading, WebP format, and defined sizes.
- Avoid unnecessary client-side re-renders through immutable state updates.
- Optimize database queries on Supabase side to avoid N+1 issues.

# Testing & Documentation (Strictly use only when told to, otherwise do not.)
- Write unit tests for public functions and components; maintain minimum 80% coverage.
- Use descriptive test names to document intent.
- Document architecture decisions and key third-party libraries used.

